Preheat your #oven{} to 220°C/200°C fan/gas mark 7.

Pop the @Irish Pork Sausages{225%grams} onto a lined #baking tray{} and roast
them on the top shelf of your oven until browned and cooked through, ~{18-20%mins}.
Turn halfway through cooking.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands after handling raw meat. The sausages are cooked
> when no longer pink in the middle.

Boil a large #pot{} of @salt{to taste} water for the potatoes.

Chop the @Baby Potatoes{400%grams} into 2cm chunks (peeling optional).

When boiling, add the potatoes to the water and cook until fork tender,
~{15-20%mins}.

Once cooked, drain in a #colander{} and return to the pot, off the heat.

> TIP: If you're in a hurry you can boil the water in your kettle.

Add a knob of @Butter{to taste} and a splash of @?water{to taste} or
@?Milk{to taste} to the potatoes.

Mash until smooth with a #potato masher{}. Season with @Salt{to taste} and
@Pepper{to taste}.

Mix the @Baby Spinach{120%grams} into the mashed potatoes. Cover to keep warm.

Halve, peel and thinly slice the @Onion{1}.

Heat a drizzle of @Oil{to taste} in a large pan on medium-high heat.

Add the onion to the pan and fry until softened, stirring occasionally,
~{4-5%mins}. This is the base of your gravy.

Lower the heat of the pan to medium and add the @Balsamic Vinegar{1%sachet}.
Cook until almost evaporated, ~{1-2%mins}.

Add @water{75%ml} (double for 4p) to the pan and bring to the boil.

Stir in the @Chicken Stock{1%sachet}, @Honey{1%sachet} and @Tomato Paste{1%pack}.

Simmer until the sauce has thickened slightly, ~{2-3%mins}.

> TIP: Add a splash of water if you feel it needs it.

Share the colcannon between your plates and serve the sausages alongside.

Spoon the gravy over the sausages and tuck in.